    1. Cubble attributes

    attributes.Rmd

    A cubble has its own attributes leaves and form:

    • leaves contains the list of variables that are time-invariant to the “spot”;
    • form specifies whether the data object is in the nested or long form.

    Nested cubble

    A nested cubble is built on top of a rowwise_df, which comes with the groups attributes, as well as the usual names, row.names, and class. Note that the class attribute contains the history class that a rowwise_df is built upon: tbl_df, tbl and data.frame. This is an example of the attributes for a nested cubble:

    nested <- climate_flat %>% 
  tamp(station)
nested
#> # Cubble: station-wise: nested form
#> # Group:  station [2]
#> # Leaves: date [date], prcp [dbl], tmax [dbl], tmin [dbl]
#>   station       lat  long elevation name                ts                
#>   <fct>       <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl> <fct>               <list>            
#> 1 ASN00001019 -14.3  127.        23 kalumburu           <tibble [366 × 4]>
#> 2 ASN00002012 -18.2  128.       422 halls creek airport <tibble [366 × 4]>
attributes(nested)
#> $names
#> [1] "station"   "lat"       "long"      "elevation" "name"      "ts"       
#> 
#> $row.names
#> [1] 1 2
#> 
#> $groups
#> # A tibble: 2 × 2
#>   station           .rows
#>   <fct>       <list<int>>
#> 1 ASN00001019         [1]
#> 2 ASN00002012         [1]
#> 
#> $leaves
#> # Leaves: 2 x 5
#>   station       lat  long elevation name               
#>   <fct>       <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl> <fct>              
#> 1 ASN00001019 -14.3  127.        23 kalumburu          
#> 2 ASN00002012 -18.2  128.       422 halls creek airport
#> 
#> $form
#> [1] "nested"
#> 
#> $class
#> [1] "cubble_df"  "rowwise_df" "tbl_df"     "tbl"        "data.frame"

    In this example, two stations recorded are ASN00001019 and ASN00002012.

    The rowwise_df class uses a group attributes to ensure each row is in its own group and this structure makes it simpler to calculate on the list. For example calculating the total precipitation can be done by:

    climate_flat %>%
  tamp(station) %>%  # cubble names the list-column as `ts` rather than `data`
  mutate(rain = sum(ts$prcp != 0, na.rm = TRUE))
#> # Cubble: station-wise: nested form
#> # Group:  station [2]
#> # Leaves: date [date], prcp [dbl], tmax [dbl], tmin [dbl]
#>   station       lat  long elevation name                ts                  rain
#>   <fct>       <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl> <fct>               <list>             <int>
#> 1 ASN00001019 -14.3  127.        23 kalumburu           <tibble [366 × 4]>    80
#> 2 ASN00002012 -18.2  128.       422 halls creek airport <tibble [366 × 4]>    69

    which matches the basic mutate style of calculation, so it is easier to remember than the purrr style syntax:

    climate_flat %>% 
  tidyr::nest(c(date, prcp, tmax, tmin)) %>% 
  mutate(rain = purrr::map_dbl(data, ~sum(.x$prcp != 0, na.rm= TRUE)))
#> Warning: All elements of `...` must be named.
#> Did you want `data = c(date, prcp, tmax, tmin)`?
#> # A tibble: 2 × 7
#>   station       lat  long elevation name                data                rain
#>   <fct>       <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl> <fct>               <list>             <dbl>
#> 1 ASN00001019 -14.3  127.        23 kalumburu           <tibble [366 × 4]>    80
#> 2 ASN00002012 -18.2  128.       422 halls creek airport <tibble [366 × 4]>    69

    The leaves attribute records the time-invariant variables to ensure a cubble can be switch between the nested and long form. The leaves attribute itself has two attributes invariant and variant, which contains both types of variables as seen below:

    leaves(nested)
#> # Leaves: 2 x 5
#>   station       lat  long elevation name               
#>   <fct>       <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl> <fct>              
#> 1 ASN00001019 -14.3  127.        23 kalumburu          
#> 2 ASN00002012 -18.2  128.       422 halls creek airport
leaves(nested) %>% invariant()
#>   station       lat      long elevation      name 
#>     "fct"     "dbl"     "dbl"     "dbl"     "fct"
leaves(nested) %>% variant()
#>   date   prcp   tmax   tmin 
#> "date"  "dbl"  "dbl"  "dbl"

    In this dataset, variables that are invariant to time include lat, long, elevation and name while those vary across time include date, prcp, tmax, and tmin. Notice that although time-variant variables are not directly shown in the nested form, they can be read from the third line of the cubble header:

    nested
#> # Cubble: station-wise: nested form
#> # Group:  station [2]
#> # Leaves: date [date], prcp [dbl], tmax [dbl], tmin [dbl]
#>   station       lat  long elevation name                ts                
#>   <fct>       <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl> <fct>               <list>            
#> 1 ASN00001019 -14.3  127.        23 kalumburu           <tibble [366 × 4]>
#> 2 ASN00002012 -18.2  128.       422 halls creek airport <tibble [366 × 4]>

    Long cubble

    A long form cubble is built from a grouped_df, instead of rowwise_df. grouped_df ensures records of all the timestamps from a “spot” is in the same group. Below prints the attributes of a long cubble:

    long <- nested %>% stretch()
long
#> # Cubble: time-wise: long form
#> # Group:  station [2]
#> # Leaves: station [fct], lat [dbl], long [dbl], elevation [dbl], name [fct]
#>    station     date        prcp  tmax  tmin
#>    <fct>       <date>     <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
#>  1 ASN00001019 2020-01-01    46  38.6  25.1
#>  2 ASN00001019 2020-01-02     0  38.8  28.1
#>  3 ASN00001019 2020-01-03   266  37.9  23.6
#>  4 ASN00001019 2020-01-04     0  34.3  26.2
#>  5 ASN00001019 2020-01-05    46  35.4  26.7
#>  6 ASN00001019 2020-01-06   760  27.5  24.8
#>  7 ASN00001019 2020-01-07  1168  31.6  23.2
#>  8 ASN00001019 2020-01-08  1178  32.7  24  
#>  9 ASN00001019 2020-01-09    48  34.2  25.1
